        title: "Fragments of <i>Othello</i> manuscript",
        printedIn: "Michael W. Price, “Rare Commentary from C.S. Lewis on Shakespeare: The Recently-Discovered <i>Othello</i> Essays,” <i>Journal of the Wooden O Symposium</i>",
        issueOrVolume: "vol. 1",
        pageRange: "43-45 and 47",
        year: 2001,
        monthAndDay: null,
        textProvided: "[{43} Lewis made a list of words or phrases in the play and titled it]<br><br>Language Places<br><br>[Lewis also made a list of editorially significant passages and titled it]<br><br>textual places<br><br>[{44}]<br><br>More important than anything else about Othello is his blackness.<br><br>We must concentrate with a primitive sharpness of vision on the physical fact: a group of men coming in by torchlight and in the midst of them, monstrous, not to be got over, the staring black face and red lips<br><br>[{45}]<br><br>foaming, furious [Turk]<br><br>chivalrous [Turk]<br><br>The idea is fascinating . . . a vague picture of unknown and possibly dangerous splendour.<br><br>The creature is noble in its own way: none the less perilous or mysterious for that.<br><br>[This] is the impression which he counts on in the minds of his audiences.<br><br>[{47} Lewis says that Jacobean audiences could not have perceived Othello]<br><br>with contempt or disgust<br><br>[because at that moment in European history]<br><br>there was no imperialism to make men think of them as members of subject races.<br><br>[Lewis’s references to Othello include:] <br><br>the Black Man<br><br>a figure<br><br>object<br><br>a thing<br><br>the creature<br><br>monstrous<br><br>the staring black face and red lips<br><br>blackamore with his flash of tooth and eye<br><br>[Lewis refers to Desdemona as]<br><br>a girl who married a sort of ogre or hobgoblin<br><br>[Lewis refers to Othello and Desdemona’s relationship as]<br><br>The Beauty and the Beast<br><br>[though he adds]<br><br>I do not mean that Shakespeare makes no more of it than that",
