        printedIn: "<i>C.S. Lewis: Images of His World,</i> eds. Clyde Kilby and Douglas Gilbert (Grand Rapids: Eerdmans)",
        issueOrVolume: null,
        pageRange: "133 (holograph)",
        year: 1973,
        monthAndDay: null,
        textProvided: "When, in haughty exultation, thou durst laugh in<br>Fortune’s face,<br>Or when thou hast sunk down weary, trampled in<br>The ceaseless race,<br>Dellius, think on this I pray thee – but the<br>Twinkling of an eye,<br>May endure thy pain or pleasure; for thou knowest<br>Thou shalt die<br>Whether on some breeze-kissed upland, with a<br>Flask of mellow wine,<br>Thou hast all the world forgotten, stretched be-<br>Neath the friendly pine,<br>Or, in foolish toil consuming all the springtime<br>Of thy life,<br>Thou hast worked for useless silver and endured<br>The bitter strife<br>Still unchanged thy doom remaineth. Thou art<br>Set towards thy goal,<br>Out into the empty breezes soon shall flicker<br>Forth thy soul,<br>Here then by the plashing streamlet fill the<br>Tinkling glass I pray<br>Bring the short lived rosy garlands, and be<br>Happy – FOR TODAY.",
        type: "Poem",
