        printedIn: "Tom Shippey, “The Lewis Diaries” in <i>C.S. Lewis and His Circle: Essays and Memoirs from the Oxford C.S. Lewis Society,</i> eds. Roger White, Judith Wolfe, and Brendan N. Wolfe (Oxford: Oxford University Press)",
        issueOrVolume: null,
        pageRange: "139",
        year: 2015,
        monthAndDay: null,
        textProvided: "[I have been in a study with somebody, and that somebody pulled off the shelf a copy of one of Wyld’s books (his <i>History of Modern Colloquial English</i>? his <i>Short History of English</i>?—one or the other) and opened it up and showed it to me. {...} inside the fly-leaf of this book was a long poem in heroic couplets, entirely abusive of Wyld. The whole thing had clearly been written in one of Wyld’s lectures, commenting on the lecture as the poem was written, and it was a pretty good poem! What’s irritating is that I’ve forgotten who it was {...} The point is, I can almost remember the end of the poem. It ends up something like]<br><br>That fearful cad and bounder H.C. Wyld.",
